Here's an example of a simple text-based game using Java:

```
import java.util.Scanner;

public class AdventureGame {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

    System.out.println("Welcome to the Adventure Game!");

    String name = getPlayerName(scanner);
    String location = "forest";

    while (true) {
      System.out.println("\nYou are currently in the " + location + ".");

      String action = getPlayerAction(scanner);
      if (action.equalsIgnoreCase("explore")) {
        location = explore(location);
      } else if (action.equalsIgnoreCase("fight")) {
        boolean won = fight();
        if (won) {
          System.out.println("Congratulations, you won the fight!");
        } else {
          System.out.println("Game over!");
          break;
        }
      } else if (action.equalsIgnoreCase("quit")) {
        System.out.println("Thanks for playing!");
        break;
      } else {
        System.out.println("Invalid action. Please try again.");
      }
    }
  }

  private static String getPlayerName(Scanner scanner) {
    System.out.println("What is your name?");
    return scanner.nextLine();
  }

  private static String getPlayerAction(Scanner scanner) {
    System.out.println("\nWhat would you like to do?");
    System.out.println("Explore");
    System.out.println("Fight");
    System.out.println("Quit");
    return scanner.nextLine();
  }

  private static String explore(String location) {
    System.out.println("You are exploring the " + location + "...");
    if (location.equalsIgnoreCase("forest")) {
      System.out.println("You found a cave!");
      return "cave";
    } else if (location.equalsIgnoreCase("cave")) {
      System.out.println("You found a treasure!");
      return "treasure";
    } else {
      return "forest";
    }
  }

  private static boolean fight() {
    System.out.println("You encountered a monster!");
    System.out.println("Do you want to fight? (y/n)");

    Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
    String answer = scanner.nextLine();

    if (answer.equalsIgnoreCase("n")) {
      System.out.println("You ran away.");
      return false;
    }

    int playerHealth = 10;
    int monsterHealth = 10;

    while (playerHealth > 0 && monsterHealth > 0) {
      int playerDamage = (int) (Math.random() * 3) + 1;
      int monsterDamage = (int) (Math.random() * 3) + 1;

      monsterHealth -= playerDamage;
      playerHealth -= monsterDamage;

      System.out.println("You hit the monster and dealt " + playerDamage + " damage!");
      System.out.println("The monster hit you and dealt " + monsterDamage + " damage!");

      System.out.println("Player health: " + playerHealth);
      System.out.println("Monster health: " + monsterHealth);
    }

    return playerHealth > 0;
  }
}
```

In this game, you play as an adventurer who can explore different locations, fight monsters, and collect treasure. Use the `getPlayerName` method to get the player's name at the beginning of the game. Use the `getPlayerAction` method to get the player's action during the game. The `explore` method generates a random event based on the location. The `fight` method lets the player fight a monster and returns true if the player wins. The game continues until the player quits or loses a fight.

